	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="TSJN-01-06-02-pb-0209">209<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=TSJN/Pages/TSJN-01-06/TSJN-01-06-02-pb-0209.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div id="TSJN-01-06-0199" class="doc">
      
      <h1>La Luzerne to Robert Livingston</h1>
      
      <div class="docbody">
        <div class="opener">
          <table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft"><span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">Monsieur</span></td>
		<td class="salutationRight">A Philadelphie le 29. Novembre 1782.</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
        </div>
        <p xml:lang="fra">Jai reu la lettre par laquelle Vous mapprens le renouvellement de la Commission de M. Jepherson et la resolution du Congrs dont elle etoit accompagne; cest avec peine que javois v ce Ministre decliner de prendre part  la ngotiation pour la paix et japprends avec un grand plaisir quil se dispose  joindre les autres Ministres que le Congrs en a chargs. Lhabilet de M. Jepherson et les services importans quil a rendus aux Etats unis sont bien connus en Europe et Vous pouvs tre persuad, Monsieur, que tous ceux qui sinteressent  la prosperit et aux avantages de ce pays ci, applaudiront au choix du Congrs.</p>
        <p xml:lang="fra">Jai lhonneur dtre avec le plus sincere et inviolable attachement Monsieur Votre trs humble et trs obissant serviteur,</p>
        <div class="closer">
          <p class="signed"><span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">Le chr de la Luzerne</span></p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="docback">
        <div class="note-source" id="TSJN-01-06-0199-sn"><p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipient's copy ]">RC</abbr> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Library of Congress ]">DLC</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 95, <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">ii</span>); in a clerks hand, signed by La Luzerne. <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ transcript ]">Tr</abbr> (<span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Library of Congress ]">DLC</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 119). An English translation is printed in Wharton, <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr. Amer. Rev.</span>, <span class="hi-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps;">vi</span>, 90.</p>
          <p>This letter is a reply to Livingstons communication of 26 Nov. 1782 in which he had informed the French minister of TJs appointment and had voiced the following comment: Mr. Jeffersons established character, his abilities, and the honorable offices he has sustained with reputation in this country, leave no room to doubt that this appointment will be highly acceptable to your court when you shall have placed them in that favorable point of view in which, I persuade myself, you take a pleasure in representing them (same, p. 81; <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ transcript ]">Tr</abbr> in <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Library of Congress ]">DLC</span>: <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Papers of the Continental Congress ]">PCC</span>, No. 119, p. 1889, in French). La Luzernes letter seems to assume that Livingston meant TJ had already accepted the appointment, but neither could have learned by 29 Nov. that this was so.</p></div>
      </div>
